# React Performance

## Derive State in Render

Compute derived values directly in the render body instead of syncing with `useEffect` + `setState`:

```tsx
// Bad: unnecessary effect and extra render
const [fullName, setFullName] = useState('');
useEffect(() => {
  setFullName(`${firstName} ${lastName}`);
}, [firstName, lastName]);

// Good: derive in render
const fullName = `${firstName} ${lastName}`;
```

## No Inline Component Definitions

Never define a component inside another component's body. This creates a new component identity on every render, causing remounts, lost state, and broken animations:

```tsx
// Bad: Avatar remounts every render
export const UserCard = ({ user }: Props) => {
  const Avatar = () => <img src={user.avatar} />;
  return <Avatar />;
};

// Good: separate component
const Avatar = ({ src }: { src: string }) => <img src={src} />;

export const UserCard = ({ user }: Props) => {
  return <Avatar src={user.avatar} />;
};
```

## Minimize 'use client' Surface

Push `'use client'` as deep as possible in the component tree. Only the leaf components that need interactivity should be client components. Keep data-fetching and layout in Server Components.

## Avoid Unstable References

Do not pass inline objects or arrow functions as props in JSX when they cause re-renders:

```tsx
// Bad: new object every render
<Box sx={{ mt: 2 }} />

// Acceptable for MUI sx (memoized internally), but avoid for custom props:
// Bad: new function every render triggers child re-render
<Button onClick={() => handleDelete(id)} />

// Good: stable callback
const onDelete = useCallback(() => handleDelete(id), [id]);
<Button onClick={onDelete} />
```

Note: MUI's `sx` prop is internally memoized, so inline `sx` objects are acceptable.

## Prefer Server Data via Props

Pass data from Server Components to Client Components via props rather than fetching on the client:

```tsx
// Good: server fetches, client renders
// page.tsx (Server Component)
const data = await fetchInstructor(id);
return <InstructorProfile data={data} />;

// InstructorProfile.tsx (Client Component)
'use client';
export const InstructorProfile = ({ data }: Props) => {
  // render with server-provided data
};
```

## Use startTransition for Non-Urgent Updates

Wrap non-urgent state updates in `startTransition` to keep the UI responsive:

```tsx
import { startTransition } from 'react';

const handleSearch = (query: string) => {
  startTransition(() => {
    setSearchResults(filterResults(query));
  });
};
```

## Use useDeferredValue for Expensive Renders

Keep inputs responsive while expensive child renders catch up:

```tsx
const [query, setQuery] = useState('');
const deferredQuery = useDeferredValue(query);

return (
  <>
    <input value={query} onChange={(e) => setQuery(e.target.value)} />
    <ExpensiveList query={deferredQuery} />
  </>
);
```

## Use Functional setState for Stable Callbacks

When the new state depends on the previous state, use functional form to avoid stale closures and unnecessary deps:

```tsx
// Bad: callback depends on count, changes every render
const increment = useCallback(() => setCount(count + 1), [count]);

// Good: stable callback, no dependency on count
const increment = useCallback(() => setCount((prev) => prev + 1), []);
```

## Lazy State Initialization

Pass a function to `useState` when the initial value is expensive to compute:

```tsx
// Bad: runs expensive computation on every render
const [state, setState] = useState(expensiveComputation());

// Good: runs once
const [state, setState] = useState(() => expensiveComputation());
```

## Hoist Default Non-Primitive Props

Inline default objects/arrays create new references on every render, breaking `React.memo`:

```tsx
// Bad: new array every render defeats memo
<MemoizedList items={items ?? []} />

// Good: stable default reference
const EMPTY_ITEMS: Item[] = [];
<MemoizedList items={items ?? EMPTY_ITEMS} />
```
